<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate rebar spacing for a concrete slab?", answer: "Rebar is laid in a grid pattern with bars running in both directions. Divide the slab width by the spacing to find bars running along the length, and divide the slab length by the spacing for bars running along the width. Add 1 to each count for the edge bar. Standard residential slabs use #4 rebar at 12-inch or 18-inch on-center (OC) spacing. Add 10% for waste from overlaps and cuts." },
  { question: "What size rebar should I use for a residential slab?", answer: "For typical 4-inch residential slabs, #4 rebar (1/2-inch diameter) at 12-inch or 18-inch spacing is standard. For driveways and garage slabs that support vehicle weight, #4 at 12-inch spacing is recommended. For sidewalks and patios, #3 rebar at 18-inch spacing is often sufficient. Always follow your local building code requirements and engineer specifications." },
  { question: "How much does rebar weigh per foot?", answer: "Rebar weight varies by size: #3 (3/8-inch) weighs 0.376 lbs/ft, #4 (1/2-inch) weighs 0.668 lbs/ft, #5 (5/8-inch) weighs 1.043 lbs/ft, #6 (3/4-inch) weighs 1.502 lbs/ft, #7 (7/8-inch) weighs 2.044 lbs/ft, and #8 (1-inch) weighs 2.670 lbs/ft. Standard rebar sticks are sold in 20-foot lengths." },
  { question: "How much overlap do rebar splices need?", answer: "The minimum lap splice length for rebar is typically 24 inches (about 40 bar diameters for #4 rebar). This overlap is where two bars are tied together to transfer load. The exact splice length depends on bar size, concrete strength, and structural requirements. Your engineer or local code will specify the exact requirement, which can range from 24 to 48 inches." },
  { question: "Should rebar be in the top or bottom of a slab?", answer: "For a standard slab-on-grade, rebar should be positioned in the bottom third of the slab thickness, typically supported by rebar chairs to maintain 2-3 inches of clear cover from the bottom. This placement provides tensile reinforcement where the concrete is most likely to crack from bending. For suspended slabs, rebar may be needed in both top and bottom depending on the engineering design." }
]) %>

